> I made sure that all properties that have no effect for a specific (fractal) noise type or with a specific combination are hidden, making it quite easy to use despite having lots of detailed handles. Give it a try :)

That definitely helps reduce the complexity! 

I'm wondering if it is possible to further reduce the complexity by exposing FastNoiseLite in a more "Godot-like" fashion. Right now a single noise node exposes every possible configuration (including FBM and Domain warping). I wonder if it would be simpler from an end user perspective using Godot-style interfaces. 

What I have in mind is exposing 4 noise classes: Noise, Cellular, Fractal, and Domain Warp. Fractal and Domain warp would themselves accept a new "noise" parameter which itself would be one of the 4 noise types. 

```
Noise {
    type = Simplex, SimplexSmooth, Perlin, Value, ValueCubic
    seed;
    frequency;
    offset;
    in_3d_space;
    ramp;
}
Cellular {
    seed;
    frequency;
    offset;
    in_3d_space;
    ramp;
    distance_function;
    jitter;
    return_type;
}
Fractal {
    noise = Noise, Cellular;
    type;
    octaves;
    lacunarity;
    gain;
    weighted_strength;
    pingpong_strength;
}
DomainWarp {
    noise = Noise, Cellular, Fractal
    type;
    amplitude;
    frequency;
}
```

From a brief look at the code, the above seems possible. Keep in mind, this is just an idea to discuss. In my mind, this would allow us to expose a relatively simple user interface, but would still allow making just as complex effects as in the original PR. It may, however, require us to work around FastNoiseLite as I see that it engrains concepts like "Fractal" pretty deeply into the concept of "noise". 

Another point for discussion, but is it useful for end users to have a choice between Simplex, SimplexSmooth, Perlin, Value, and Value cubic? The difference to end users will be quite minor and may not to even be noticeable to many. My guess is that 99% of users will be fine with Simplex and won't ever need to look at the other types (especially when using FBM where the peculiar visual artifacts of simplex are less pronounced).

Rebased and moved the following methods into the noise interface:

```
virtual real_t get_noise_1d(real_t p_x) = 0;

virtual real_t get_noise_2dv(Vector2 p_v) = 0;
virtual real_t get_noise_2d(real_t p_x, real_t p_y) = 0;

virtual real_t get_noise_3dv(Vector3 p_v) = 0;
virtual real_t get_noise_3d(real_t p_x, real_t p_y, real_t p_z) = 0;
```
get_noise_4d is not (yet) part of it since FastNoiseLite unfortunately does not support 4D noise atm and I don’t like to add a function to the interface which is not fully implemented by the new default noise implementation. But keep in mind this doesn't stop other noise generators to provide this functionality, it is just not a mandatory requirement for a generator extending the noise interface.

