> Although these are normally applied to each function individually, @akien-mga noticed they can be applied to whole classes - whenever the class is returned in a function it will emit the nodiscard warning in this case. This is much less verbose and enables us to catch errors in the main classes, at the cost of some possible false positives.

To clarify what this does for those not familiar (we had to look up some Reddit threads and do some local testing to figure it out):

- `[[nodiscard]]` applied to a method will raise a warning when that method is used and the return value is discard. E.g.:

```cpp
[[nodiscard]] int some_func() {
	return 42;
}

void main() {
	some_func();
}
```

- `[[nodiscard]]` applied to a class/struct will raise a warning whenever a method returning an object of that class has its value discarded. E.g.:

```cpp
class [[nodiscard]] SomeClass {
	SomeClass() {}
};

SomeClass some_func() {
	return SomeClass();
}

void main() {
	some_func();
}
```

This PR implements the latter for core math types, i.e. it's the same as if we added the `[[nodiscard]]` attribute to all functions in the codebase that return `Vector2`, `Vector3`, `Transform3D`, etc.

That **doesn't** apply to members functions of these core class which return a non-Godot type, e.g. `int` or `real_t`. These will still need a per-function attribute which will be added where relevant in a future PR. But it still covers a lot of cases and most importantly the cases discussed in the OP where there can be confusion between a method that returns a new object of that class or modifies the current object in-place.

`[[nodiscard]]` warnings are raised via `-Wunused-result` which should be enabled by default for GCC and Clang (to be tested for MSVC). They can be disabled where relevant with a `-Wno-unused-result` pragma, or preferentially by casting to `void` and adding an explanatory comment (as done here with the `_ALLOW_DISCARD_` macro added for clarity's sake).

