Overall it seems like an OK solution but we'd want a way to respect `rendering/textures/canvas_textures/default_texture_filter`.

*Edit:* It looks to me like the logic already aims at respective the default texture filter/repeat, but there seems to be a bug.

```cpp
void CanvasItem::_refresh_texture_filter_cache() {
	if (!is_inside_tree()) {
		return;
	}

	if (texture_filter == TEXTURE_FILTER_PARENT_NODE) {
		CanvasItem *parent_item = get_parent_item();
		if (parent_item) {
			texture_filter_cache = parent_item->texture_filter_cache;
		} else {
			texture_filter_cache = RS::CANVAS_ITEM_TEXTURE_FILTER_DEFAULT;
		}
	} else {
		texture_filter_cache = RS::CanvasItemTextureFilter(texture_filter);
	}
}
```
In this code, once it reaches the root node, it will assign `RS::CANVAS_ITEM_TEXTURE_FILTER_DEFAULT` which is 0, i.e. the same as `TEXTURE_FILTER_PARENT_NODE`. So in the end it's still "no idea", we're at the root viewport yet but we still don't have a clear texture filter value to work with.

*Edit 2:* I did a deep dive through the rendering code and overall, I don't understand why the bug happens in the first place. Everything is set so that the default texture filter and repeat mode is respected. It's set in EditorNode on start, so it should work fine (albeit it should likely be made a `_RST` macro so it forces a restart when changed). But somehow it works in the CanvasItemEditor but not in other plugins.

Also, another idea could be to make it always use Linear in this kind of preview. I think previewing high res scaled assets with Linear is likely less bad than low res normal sized or scaled assets with Nearest?

